3.) Split the Data into test/training Data

split1<- sample(c(rep('Train', 0.8 * nrow(breast.cancer.wisconsin)), 
                  rep('Test', 0.2 * nrow(breast.cancer.wisconsin))))
table(split1)
## split1
##  Test Train 
##   136   546
x_train<-breast.cancer.wisconsin[split1=='Train', ]
y_train<-Class[split1=='Train']
x_test<-breast.cancer.wisconsin[split1=='Test',]
y_test<-Class[split1=='Test']
attach(x_train)

4.) Create a Logistic Regression Classification Model including all Variables

breast_cancer_model <- glm(y_train~.,data = x_train,
                           subset = -c(`Sample Code Number`),family = binomial)

4a.This model is not great it has a 58.7% accuracy rate with 0.413 test error.
the Confusion matrix is shown above. The Statistically Significant predictors are Clump Thickness, Uniformity of Cell Shape, Marginal Adhesion, and Bland Chromatin based on the low pvalues.

#5 KNN

set.seed(1)

breast_cancer_knn = knn(x_train, x_test, y_train, k=sqrt(length(y_train)))
table(breast_cancer_knn, y_test)
##                  y_test
## breast_cancer_knn  2  4
##                 2 86 34
##                 4  5 11
mean(breast_cancer_knn==y_test)
## [1] 0.7132353
mean(breast_cancer_knn!=y_test)
## [1] 0.2867647
best_mean <- 0
best_k<-0
for (i in 1:100)
{
  bcn_knn <- knn(x_train,x_test,y_train, k = i)
  if (mean(bcn_knn==y_test)>best_mean)
  {
    best_mean <- mean(bcn_knn==y_test)
    best_k <- i
  }
  
}

best_k
## [1] 4
best_mean
## [1] 0.7352941
bc_knn = knn(x_train, x_test, y_train, k =best_k)
table(bc_knn, y_test)
##       y_test
## bc_knn  2  4
##      2 72 25
##      4 19 20
mean(bc_knn==y_test)
## [1] 0.6764706
mean(bc_knn!=y_test)
## [1] 0.3235294

This model performs a bit better than the Logistic Regression.
The test errors of both knn models are lower than the logistic regression. I created a for loop to run through k values between 1 and 100 and created a knn model with the best value of k providing the lowest Test error of 0.287

#7 QDA

breast_cancer_qda=qda(y_train~.,data = x_train,
                           subset = -c(`Sample Code Number`))



bc_qda_pred=predict(breast_cancer_qda, x_test)

bc_qda_class=bc_qda_pred$class

#8 The LDA and QDA models perform significantly better than the other models. They are very similar in design and show that the data is more linearly dependent. As mentioned before the LDA performs the best out of all models. I experimented most with the knn model in which I was able to see that the best value for k peaked around 50, but still did not do nearly as well as the LDA and QDA models.
